            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Another option that affects terminal buffers is the `'scrolloff'`. When leaving terminal mode, the buffer may be unintentionally scrolled (and it also scrolls back when returning to terminal mode). To reproduce, just run a command long enough to fill the window's height, and run `clear`. On terminal mode, the cursor is at the top:\r\n\r\n![image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/54bec23e-026c-4996-bf67-c2b3e841a88d)\r\n\r\nBut after returning to normal mode, `'scrolloff'` is applied:\r\n\r\n![image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c9ca33ea-d698-4c31-8eb7-ced1b585b71a)\r\n\r\nGiven that this PR already leans into better defaults, I wonder if it makes sense to also set `scrolloff=0`?\r\n",
